    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies, friend! My mind, it seems, has been thoroughly overrun by the sheer chaotic energy of the local goblin population. They are *everywhere*, you see. One moment I'm discussing municipal codes, the next I'm picturing a horde of them trying to set up a tiny, ill-advised market stall right on the corner of a sidewalk!\n\nTo get you the precise technical requirements for encroachment permits in Portland's R-5 zone, you absolutely must consult the official Portland Zoning Code (Title 33). Specifically, you need to investigate sections dealing with \"Accessory Uses,\" \"Front Yard Setbacks,\" and any specific overlays that might apply to mixed-use development within R-5.\n\nRegarding the *permit* for encroachment, this usually falls under a variance or a special use permit application, depending on how far the grocery store wants to push its little shop into the pedestrian buffer. A standard setback is the baseline, but if you want to deviate—if you want your grocery to be as close to the curb as a goblin is to a shiny, unattended pile of stolen goods—you need formal approval.\n\nI strongly advise contacting the Bureau of Development Services (BDS) directly. They are",
